Author: R. MASON
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: `To go around the side of; to go along a hill-side. (tramping.) To sidle a hill; to sidle along a valley (not on the ridge, not on the valley floor, but along the hillside.) In common use among trampers. The term was not understood by Dr. I.V. Newman, lecturer in Botany, V.U.C., an Australian.'
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1953
Source: Musterer on Molesworth
Author: STRONACH
Vol / Page: 23
Edition:
Quote: Most of the Clarence block is `sidled'. That is to say, the spurs are so big that it is necessary to have several men sidling on the `face' or side of each spur. I have seen as many as ten men on a face sidling along about half a mile apart. The man on the top beat, in all but exceptional circumstances, keeps a little in front, and each man down the face is a little behind the man above.
Notes:

